Rating: 3
This is very close to the classic recipe, and it's really not a recipe but a treatment. One should use mineral water (salt not needed, therefore) and unrefined sugar. I see some good cooks here who instinctively substitued brown sugar or the like. I know French cooks who prefer honey. If your carrots are mature, you may wish to cut them into "allumettes" (matchsticks) instead of slices. There are endless variations: try adding a tablespoon or so of Pernod, Cointreau,or sweet vermouth, or, a slight grating of fresh nutmeg or white peppercorns. Other "fines herbes", dill in particular, are also frequently substituted for the parsley. Bon appetit!

Rating: 4
I wanted something quick and uncomplicated that would add color to the plate. Using brown sugar and chicken broth, this was the perfect choice. The meal was Chopped Vegetable Salad with Feta and Olives, Smashed Baby Red Potatoes with Ancho Chiles and Dry Jack Cheese, and Roast Beef Tenderloin with Port Sauce (all on this site). Elegant and so easy. Much can be done ahead of time and I was away from the guests all of 35 minutes.

